pgTitle: Table of handgun and rifle cartridges

rows.text: Bottlenecked high velocity PDW cartridge designed by Heckler & Koch in conjunction with the Heckler & Koch MP7 personal defense weapon.
NATO (1980), 2nd gen. Current NATO service including M16 rifle, Steyr AUG, SA80, FAMAS, Heckler & Koch G36. Similar, but not interchangeable with .223 Rem.
Swiss military version of the 5.56×45mm NATO / 223 Remington. For SIG SG 550 and variants.
Bottlenecked high velocity PDW cartridge designed by FN Herstal. Designed in response to NATO requests for a replacement for the 9×19mm cartridge. Frequently used in the FN Five-seven Pistol.
aka 6.2×57mm RWS. Necked down 6.5×57mm. The 6mm Remington is a carbon copy.
Service cartridge of the United States Navy and Marine Corps from 1895
Benchrest cartridge - "the most accurate round ever developed." .22 PPC case necked up to 6mm.
Same cartridge as .244 Remington and interchangeable. Rifles marked .244 Remington may not stabilize heaviest 6mm Remington bullets.
Norma's redesigned of the Remington 6mm BR in order to utilize VLD bullets.
Developed by David Tubb for his Tubb 2000 rifle.
Specifically designed and optimized for 300-1000m competition.
Developed by Alexander Arms as a "low recoil, high accuracy, long-range cartridge for the AR-15 platform."
.225 Winchester case necked up to 6.5mm and then blown out.
aka 6.5×50mm Japanese. Used in Arisaka Japanese service rifles.
Once chambered for Kurz short-action carbines.
also 6.5×57mmR. a.k.a. 6.5×57mm RWS. Currently loaded by Prvi Partizan, RWS, and Sellier & Bellot
Developed by Remington with members of 5th Special Forces Group.
a.k.a. 7.5×54mm French. Used in fusil-mitrailleur mle 1924.
Based on 7.63×25mm Mauser. Most famous for use in Tokarev TT pistol. Also used in several Soviet submachine guns, including the PPSh-41.
Intermediate cartridge concept, following 7.92×33mm Kurz and preceding 5.56×45mm NATO. SKS and AK-47 USSR service rifles.
NATO (1953), T65. Current NATO service including M14 rifle, Heckler & Koch G3, FN FAL. Very similar to .308 Win.
Designed for the Mosin–Nagant Russian service rifle. Oldest cartridge still in official military use, used in SVD Dragunov with Russia and the PSL rifles with many other countries.
aka 30 Mauser. Based on 7.65×25mm Borchardt. Most famous for use in Mauser C96 pistol. Basis for 7.62×25mm Tokarev round.
a.k.a. 7,65 Parabellum, 7.65mm Luger, .30 Parabellum and (wrongly) .30 Luger.
Used for kbk ppanc wz.35 anti-tank rifle.
First assault rifle round, used in MKb 42.
a.k.a. 8×50mmR French. Adapted from the 11mm Gras. The first smokeless powder cartridge for military use, started the small-bore smokeless revolution.

aka 8×57 J, 7.92×57mm Mauser, 8×57mm Mauser, 8mm Mauser. Original smaller-bore specification. Bullet diameter and chamber pressure were increased in 1905, becoming 8×57 IS. Vintage rifles in this older chambering will dangerously accept modern 8×57 IS.
a.k.a. 8×57 JS, 7.92×57mm Mauser, 8×57mm Mauser, 8mm Mauser. Dangerously-similar to the original, smaller-bore 1888 rimless 8×57 I a.k.a. 8×57 J. Also similar to the rimmed 8×57 IRS a.k.a. 8×57 JRS.
aka 8×58mmR Danish Krag. Danish service rifle 1889-1945
aka 8×60mm RWS. Civilian 8mm Mauser. Comes in J and S bullets, rimmed or rimless case. Still loaded by RWS, Prvi Partizan.
Also 8x65mmR. Comes in J and S bullets. Based on 9.3x62mm and 9.3x74mmR.
Developed for the FN Browning 1903 Model pistol
Bottle necked cartridge for the Webley-Mars Automatic Pistol.
Also available in a rimmed version.
Scandinavian 8×57mm variant currently offered by Norma
Designed by Otto Bock for use in magazine rifles, e.g. Mauser 98, for African game.
aka 9.5×56mm Mannlicher–Schönauer, 9.5×56.7mm and .375 Nitro Express Rimless.
Once popular with European hunters in Africa and India. Approaches .375 H&H power with top loads.
The first French brass cartridge for military use. Blackpowder. Replaced by 8mm Lebel.
The first black powder cartridge adopted in large numbers by the unified German Army, it was used in the 1871 and 1871/84 rifles.
The first black powder cartridge adopted in large numbers by the Japanese Army, it was used in the Murata rifle, a hybrid of French Gras and German Mausers 1871 and 1871/84 rifles.
Necked-down .22 Hornet. Watch out for differences between older .17 Ackley Hornet and current .17 Hornady Hornet. No CIP or SAAMI specs found.
High-performance approx {{convert|4000|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}} in a small case.
First centerfire cartridge widely adapted for varmint hunting.
Rimfire. Most common cartridge in the world (by units sold). Blackpowder propellant charge listed - smokeless likely lower.
Rimfire. Oldest commercial cartridge being loaded today. Blackpowder propellant charge listed - smokeless likely lower.
Smallest belted magnum case available commercially.
aka .240 H&H Magnum Rimless, .240 Magnum Flanged or .240 Super Express
from Halger Arms Co. of Hamburg
Handgun round, popular for small size and weight.
.357 Magnum case necked down to .257". a.k.a. 256 Winchester. Obsolete handgun and lever action round.
Belted. First of Weatherby's line of necked-down 300 H&H-based magnums.
aka .275 Belted Magnum. Also comes in rimmed version called "Flanged". Necked down .375 H&H Magnum
Former wildcat now registered by Nosler with SAAMI.
a.k.a. 7mm FN Short. Intermediate round adopted in 1951.
.280 Nitro, .280 Rimless Nitro Express Ross (CIP) and .280 Rimless. Once manufactured by Remington and Winchester.
Billed as "The worlds only 30-caliber big-game cartridge for the light weight AR-15 platform."
Wildcat handgun cartridge, based on a shortened .30-30 Winchester.
a.k.a. .30 Winchester Centerfire and .30 WCF. First smokeless cartridge designed for big game hunting.
Belted. Necked-down 378 Weatherby Magnum, developed for 1000-yard performance. Was military-only from 1959 to 1996.
Developed for suppressed CQB as a sub sonic round. Supersonic is also available.
Belted. a.k.a. 300 H&H Super a.k.a. Holland's Super 30.
Beltless, rebated rim. Remington Short Action Ultra Magnum.
Beltless, rebated rim. Fastest cartridge for Nosler's 210-grain AccuBond Long-Range G1=0.730 0.308" bullet.
Designed for quiet, accurate, subsonic applications. Year is for homologation by CIP - earlier proprietary and wildcat versions existed.
Necked-down .338 Norma Mag. Selected by US Special Forces in 2016.
Rimmed version of the .308 Winchester, for use in lever-action rifles.
Based upon a slightly shortened .308 Winchester cases with FTX bullets and special powder to approach .308 ballistics from a Marlin lever-action rifle.
Belted. European cartridge designed for the US market.
a.k.a. .32 Short and .32 Long. Introduced in Smith & Wesson's Model 2 revolver.
a.k.a. .32 WSL or .32 SL. Obsolete. Only chambered commercially in the Winchester Model 1905 rifle.
Lever action, rimmed. Developed for the Winchester Model 1894.
Wildcat designed to derive maximum effect from long, aerodynamic bullets.
Rimmed lever action cartridge designed for the Marlin Model 336.
Beltless, rebated rim cartridge based on the .300 Remington Ultra Magnum.
One of the most powerful rimmed cartridges ever used in a lever rifle.
a.k.a. .35 WSL or .35 SL. Obsolete. Only chambered commercially in the Winchester Model 1905 rifle.
a.k.a. .351 WSL or .351 SL. Only chambered commercially in the Winchester Model 1907 rifle.
Hornady and Steyr announced this cartridges at the 2000 Shot Show, based on a concept by Jeff Cooper.
The rimmed .375 H&H Flanged Magnum for double-guns and the .375 H&H Belted Rimless Magnum with a headspacing belt for magazine-fed rifles were released simultaneously in 1912.
Developed in collaboration between Ruger and Hornady.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}
A beltless, rebated rim cartridge developed by Remington Arms by necking up the .300 Remington Ultra Magnum case.
Belted magnum based on the .375 H&H, blown out and reshouldered.
4th or 5th oldest commercial cartridge being loaded today.
.45 ACP case necked down to .40 caliber.
Rimmed. a.k.a. .401 WSL or .401 SL. Obsolete. Only chambered commercially in the Winchester Model 1910 and the Belgian Clement-Neumann rifle.
Most powerful rimmed cartridge designed specifically for lever-action rifles. Obsolete.
Used in Cheyenne Tactical's M200 Intervention, and M310 rifles.
Designed as an alternative to the .50 BMG for sniper rifles.
Later used parent cartridge of the .338 Lapua Magnum.
Blackpowder Russian service rifle. a.k.a. 4.2 Line Berdan. Designed by American inventor/soldier Hiram Berdan, adopted by Russia in trapdoor 1868 and turnbolt 1870 Berdan Rifles.
a.k.a. .44 Rimfire, .44 Long Rimfire, or 11×23mmR. Obsolete blackpowder cartridge.
a.k.a. .44 Remington Magnum. Lengthened .44 Special. Crossover rifle/handgun cartridge.
First developed for lever-action, later used in revolver.
Lengthened .44 Magnum case, but a lever-action rifle cartridge.
Automatic Colt Pistol, first self-loading U.S. Army pistol round.
a.k.a. .45 Long Colt or .45 LC. Used in both handgun and rifle.
a.k.a. .45 Winchester Magnum. Lengthened and strengthened .45 ACP.
Hybrid of the .460 S&W Magnum and the .308 Winchester. Designed to provide a .45 caliber capability to the AR-10 platform.
a.k.a. .45-70 Government. One of the oldest centerfire cartridges still in commercial production.
a.k.a. .450 Boxer and .450 Revolver. Obsolete blackpowder handgun cartridge.
Developed by hornady as a straight walled rifle round almost identical to .460 S&W Magnum
Lever action round. Shortened .458 Winchester Magnum case, designed to match .45-70 performance.
J. Rigby smokeless cartridge based upon .450 Black Powder Express.
Lengthened .45 Colt, most powerful handgun round until the 1990s.
a.k.a. .46 Short, .46 Remington Carbine. First large-caliber metallic handgun cartridge. Blackpowder.
Used in Heavy Machine Guns and anti-materiel rifles.
a.k.a. 50 Remington Pistol Navy Model 1867 and 50 Remington (M71 Army). Rimmed case 0.875" in length. Obsolete blackpowder/smokeless handgun cartridge.
The mainstay of the American bison (buffalo) hunter. Blackpowder/smokeless.
One of the most powerful handgun-specific cartridges.
The first black powder cartridge for British military use. Later loaded smokeless.

Rimmed. The second blackpowder (later smokeless) cartridge for British military use. Evolved from the .577 Snider case, lengthened and necked down to .45 (nominal) caliber. Used in the Martini rifles from 1871 to the present.
Used in Heavy Machine Guns, AT-rifles and anti-materiel rifles.
Used in Heavy Machine Guns, AT-rifles and anti-materiel rifles.
Largest centerfire rifle cartridge as of 2018
Designed to have significantly less recoil than other 50 caliber handguns
